{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}} [[File:Adrian ward changing grammars.jpg|thumb|100px|Adrian ward at Changing Grammars, Hamburg 2004]] '''Adrian Ward''' (born 1976 in [[Bishop Auckland]], England) is a [[software art]]ist and musician. He is known for his [[generative art]] software products released through his company Signwave, and as one third of the [[techno]] [[Gabber music|gabba]] [[ambient music|ambient]] group, [[Slub (band)|Slub]].<ref>Shulgin, A. (2003). Listen to the tools, interview with Alex McLean and Adrian Ward. In read_me 2.3 reader. NIFCA.</ref> His theoretical approach to generative and software art guides his practice,<ref>Cox, G., McLean, A., and Ward, A. (2000). The Aesthetics of Generative Code. In International Conference on Generative Art. </ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GsueBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA212&dq=%22adrian+ward%22+software+art&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjexabNwbvSAhVrAcAKHU3VBBo4ChDoAQgZMAA#v=onepage&q=%22adrian%20ward%22%20software%20art&f=false|title=Digital Media and Technologies for Virtual Artistic Spaces|last=Dew|first=Harrison|date=2013-02-28|publisher=IGI Global|isbn=9781466629622|language=en}}</ref> including contributing to the early principles of the [[livecoding]] movement.<ref>Ward, A., Rohrhuber, J., Olofsson, F., McLean, A., Griffiths, D., Collins, N., and Alexander, A. (2004). Live Algorithm Programming and a Temporary Organisation for its Promotion. In Goriunova, O. and Shulgin, A., editors, read_me – Software Art and Cultures. </ref>
Adrian co-won the 2001 [[Transmediale]] software art award in [[Berlin]], alongside [[Netochka Nezvanova (author)|Netochka Nezvanova]] for his well-known<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=edFKCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA146&dq=adrian+ward+auto&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=adrian%20ward%20auto&f=false|title=Interface Cultures: Artistic Aspects of Interaction|last=Sommerer|first=Christa|last2=Mignonneau|first2=Laurent|last3=King|first3=Dorothée|date=2017-03-03|publisher=transcript Verlag|isbn=9783839408841|language=en}}</ref> Auto-Illustrator<ref>Ward, A., Levin, G., Lia, and Meta. 4x4 Generative Design (with Auto-Illustrator, Java, DBN, Lingo): Life/Oblivion. Apress.</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LFJ3ashVBuIC&pg=PA36&dq=adrian+ward+auto&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=adrian%20ward%20auto&f=false|title=Software Studies: A Lexicon|last=Fuller|first=Matthew|date=2008-01-01|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=9780262062749|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2tffHcKQ1R4C&pg=PA282&dq=adrian+ward+auto&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=adrian%20ward%20auto&f=false|title=Self-Reference in the Media|last=Nöth|first=Winfried|last2=Bishara|first2=Nina|date=2007-01-01|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=9783110198836|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=RarTbJ84EnMC&pg=PA14&dq=adrian+ward+auto&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=adrian%20ward%20auto&f=false|title=Software Takes Command|last=Manovich|first=Lev|date=2013-07-04|publisher=A&amp;C Black|isbn=1623567459|language=en}}</ref> parody of [[Adobe Illustrator]], off-the-shelf generative software that takes control over the artwork produced with it.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9BWaEXLrA4IC&pg=PA122&dq=%22adrian+ward%22+software+art&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22adrian%20ward%22%20software%20art&f=false|title=Hot-Wiring Your Creative Process: Strategies for print and new media designers|last=Cloninger|first=Curt|date=2006-10-03|publisher=New Riders|isbn=9780132798228|language=en}}</ref> Auto-Illustrator has earned prestigious digital arts awards<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dRIWUtp8UCIC&pg=PT325&dq=adrian+ward+auto&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=adrian%20ward&f=false|title=Thoughtful Interaction Design: A Design Perspective on Information Technology|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=9780262296922|language=en}}</ref> including an honorary mention at the 2001 [[Prix Ars Electronica]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xjF-E7TzADcC&pg=RA1-PA116&dq=adrian+ward+auto&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=adrian%20ward%20auto&f=false|title=Cyberarts 2001|last=Leopoldseder|first=Hannes|last2=Schöpf|first2=Christine|date=2001-09-04|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=9783211836286|language=de}}</ref> He is also a board member of the [[UK Museum of Ordure]], an ongoing collaborative art project with [[Stuart Brisley]] and Geoff Cox.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xhT7zp4rIukC&pg=PA160&dq=%22adrian+ward%22+software+art&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXn5K0wbvSAhXLI8AKHeBXBuwQ6AEIQDAH#v=onepage&q=%22adrian%20ward%22%20software%20art&f=false|title=Issues in Curating Contemporary Art and Performance|last=Rugg|first=Judith|last2=Sedgwick|first2=Michèle|date=2007-01-01|publisher=Intellect Books|isbn=9781841501628|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sXbUGHzv8o8C&pg=PT330&dq=%22adrian+ward%22+art&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjRy-zDwrvSAhULIcAKHek3Dts4FBDoAQgfMAE#v=onepage&q=%22adrian%20ward%22%20art&f=false|title=Engineering Nature: Art & Consciousness in the Post-biological Era|last=Ascott|first=Roy|date=2006-01-01|publisher=Intellect Books|isbn=9781841501284|language=en}}</ref>
